===Etymology===
From {{etyl|NL.|en}} {{m|la|logarithmus}}, term coined by Scot mathematician {{w|John Napier}} from {{etyl|grc|en}} {{m|grc|λόγος||word, reason}} and {{m|grc|ἀριθμός||number}}; compare {{m|en|rational number}}, from analogous {{etyl|la|-}}.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|mathematics}} For a number <math>x</math>, the [[power]] to which a given ''[[base]]'' number must be raised in order to obtain <math>x</math>. Written <math>\log_b x</math>. For example, <math>\log_{10} 1000 = 3</math> because <math>10^3 = 1000</math> and <math>\log_2 16 = 4</math> because <math>2^4 = 16</math>.
#: ''For a currency which uses denominations of 1, 2, 5, 10, 20, 50, 100, 200, 500, 1000, etc., each jump in the base-10 [[logarithm]] from one denomination to the next higher is either 0.3010 or 0.3979.''

